#: Game.Levels.KnightsAndKnaves2
msgid "Say we have an islander ôÏ0 who could be a knight or a knave.\n"
"\n"
"ôÏ1 is represented as\n"
"ôÏ2\n"
"where having the proposition ôÏ3 being true means the islander ôÏ4 is a knight and having the proposition ôÏ5 being false means the islander ôÏ6 is a knave.\n"
"\n"
"Now, we intrepret having a proof of ôÏ7 as ôÏ8 being a knight, and having a proof of ôÏ9 as ôÏ10 being a knave.\n"
"\n"
"From this, every islander being a knight or a knave is represented as follows:\n"
"ôÏ11\n"
"\n"
"Knights always tell the truth, so if ôÏ12 makes some statement ôÏ13 we have that ôÏ14 being a knight implies that the statement ôÏ15 is true\n"
"ôÏ16\n"
"Moreover, the statement ôÏ17 being true means that ôÏ18 is telling the truth, i.e. is a knight\n"
"ôÏ19\n"
"which can be combined as\n"
"ôÏ20\n"
"\n"
"Similarly for ôÏ21 being a knave which implies that the statement ôÏ22 is false\n"
"ôÏ23\n"
"Moreover, the statement ôÏ24 being false means that ôÏ25 is lying, i.e. is a knave\n"
"ôÏ26\n"
"which are combined as\n"
"ôÏ27\n"
"\n"
"No islander can be a knight and a knave at the same time because\n"
"ôÏ28\n"
"is false.\n"
"\n"
"This representation captures the rules of the knights and knaves puzzle which are:\n"
"- Every islander is either a knight or a knave\n"
"- No islander is both a knight and a knave at the same time\n"
"- Knights always tell the truth, knaves always lie.\n"
"\n"
"Note that you could also take a more explicit truth table approach, where you list all the cases in a truth table and eliminate the cases which contradict the rules of the game (e.g ôÏ29 being a knight but ôÏ30's statement being false). If you are left with one possibility then the puzzle has a unique solution, otherwise it has multiple solutions.\n"
"This can be done in [prolog](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oEAa2pQKqQU) and [other provers](https://summerofgodel.blogspot.com/2019/04/part-6-propositional-logic-approach-to.html)"
